Target Brazil E commerce SQL Case Study (2016–2018)
1. Project Overview
This project analyzes Target’s e commerce operations in Brazil between 2016 and 2018 using SQL. The objective is to extract business insights related to customer behavior, order trends, revenue movement, logistics performance, and payment patterns, and translate them into actionable recommendations.
________________________________________
2. Business Objectives
•	Understand customer distribution and ordering behavior across Brazil
•	Identify time based trends and seasonality in orders
•	Analyze revenue, freight cost, and delivery efficiency
•	Evaluate payment behavior and financial risk
•	Provide strategic, data driven recommendations
________________________________________
3. Dataset & Schema
Tables Used
•	customers
•	orders
•	order_items
•	payments
•	products
•	sellers
•	reviews
•	geolocation
Key Notes
•	Analysis is primarily at state and time level
•	Geolocation table is used only for location-based or distance analysis, not for state-level aggregation
________________________________________
4. Analysis Sections & SQL Tasks
4.1 Initial Data Exploration
Objective: Understand data structure and coverage
SQL Tasks:
•	Inspect column data types (customers table)
•	Identify order date range
•	Count distinct customer cities and states
Business Insight:
•	Orders span from 2016 to 2018
•	Customer presence across most Brazilian states, heavily skewed toward São Paulo (SP)
________________________________________
4.2 Order Trend & Seasonality Analysis
Objective: Understand how demand changes over time
SQL Tasks:
•	Year wise order growth
•	Month on month order trends
•	Time of day segmentation (Dawn / Morning / Afternoon / Night)
Key Findings:
•	Overall upward trend in number of orders
•	Peak demand observed in May, July, and August
•	Majority of orders placed in Afternoon and Night
________________________________________
4.3 Customer & Market Distribution
Objective: Evaluate market penetration
SQL Tasks:
•	Distribution of customers across states
•	Month on month orders per state
Key Findings:
•	São Paulo (SP) dominates customer base (~41K customers)
•	Other states show significantly lower engagement
Business Interpretation:
•	Over dependence on SP market
•	Large untapped potential in low order states
________________________________________
4.4 Revenue & Economic Impact Analysis
Objective: Analyze money flow
SQL Tasks:
•	Total and average order value per state
•	Freight cost analysis per state
•	% increase in order cost from 2017 → 2018 (Jan–Aug)
Key Findings:
•	Revenue growth aligned with increasing order volume
•	Freight cost contributes significantly to total order value
________________________________________
4.5 Logistics & Delivery Performance
Objective: Evaluate delivery efficiency
SQL Tasks:
•	Actual delivery time calculation
•	Difference between estimated and actual delivery
•	States with fastest & slowest deliveries
•	States where delivery is faster than estimate
Key Findings:
•	Average delivery delay difference ≈ 0.1 days (very efficient)
•	High service quality but increased freight cost
________________________________________
4.6 Payment Behavior Analysis
Objective: Assess financial risk and customer preference
SQL Tasks:
•	Month on month orders by payment type
•	Orders by number of installments
Key Findings:
•	Extremely low payment gap relative to total revenue
•	Installment based payments widely used
Business Insight:
•	Low financial risk
•	Strong customer trust in platform
________________________________________
5. Key Business Insights
•	Strong growth trajectory in Brazilian e commerce demand
•	Seasonal demand not fully leveraged
•	Heavy dependence on São Paulo market
•	Excellent delivery performance at high freight cost
•	Payment system is robust and low risk
________________________________________
6. Actionable Recommendations
Inventory & Sales Strategy
•	Align inventory with seasonal demand patterns
•	Use off season sales for stock clearance (FIFO/LIFO discipline)
Marketing & Growth
•	Increase advertising and promotions in low performing states
•	Design time based offers (Afternoon vs Night shoppers)
Logistics Optimization
•	Invest in regional warehouses to reduce freight cost
•	Balance delivery speed with operational cost efficiency
Market Expansion
•	Reduce over reliance on São Paulo
•	Strengthen presence in emerging states through localized campaigns
________________________________________
7. Conclusion
This SQL project demonstrates how structured data analysis can translate raw transactional data into strategic business decisions. By addressing seasonality gaps, logistics cost, and market imbalance, Target can significantly improve profitability and customer reach in Brazil.

